# Add caelestia window icon when installing UI applications

When adding a new GUI application to the NixOS config (e.g. to `home.packages` or `environment.systemPackages`), also add a matching Material Symbols entry to `programs.caelestia.settings.bar.workspaces.windowIcons` in:

`modules/desktop/hyprland/programs/caelestia/default.nix`

Each entry maps the application's Hyprland window class (regex) to a Material Symbols (Rounded) icon name. Browse icon names at https://fonts.google.com/icons.

If the `windowIcons` list does not yet exist, add it inside `bar.workspaces`:

```nix
bar.workspaces = {
  # ...existing options...
  windowIcons = [
    { regex = "obsidian"; icon = "edit_note"; }
  ];
};
```

To add to an existing list, append a new attrset:

```nix
{ regex = "steam(_app_(default|[0-9]+))?"; icon = "sports_esports"; }
{ regex = "(firefox|vivaldi|helium|google-chrome|microsoft-edge)"; icon = "public"; }
{ regex = "(kitty|alacritty|wezterm)"; icon = "terminal"; }
{ regex = "discord|slack"; icon = "chat"; }
{ regex = "spotify"; icon = "music_note"; }
{ regex = "(nautilus|thunar|org.kde.dolphin)"; icon = "folder"; }
```

Pick an icon that visually represents the app's purpose (globe for browsers, terminal for terminals, gamepad for game launchers, edit_note for note apps, etc.).

This does **not** apply to CLI-only tools or background services — only applications that open a visible window.
